 of brambles and undergrowth) + <i>feld</i> ‘pasture, open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":87,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":96,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrice Glanville was born about 1128, in England, her father, William de Glanville Lord of Bromholm, was 40 and her mother, Beatrice Sackville, was 35. She married Hugh de Legh about 1151, in Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1128–":"umbes 1128–Surnud","1110–1147":"1110–1147","1128–Female":"1128–Surnud","1130–1167":"1130–1167","1126–1151":"1126–1151","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1090–1147":"1090–1147","1095–1195":"1095–1195","about 1151":"umbes 1151","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1151":"1151","1095":"1095","1217":"1217","1128":"1128","1215"